summary:
Acknowledges Bosnia and Herzegovina's support for the EU force and continued NATO presence as successors to SFOR;

Pays tribute to Member States participating in the multinational stabilization force;

Welcomes the EU's intention to launch a military operation in Bosnia and Herzegovina from December 2004;

Authorizes a multinational stabilization force (EUFOR) under EU command for 12 months, as SFOR's successor, to fulfill missions related to the Peace Agreement's Annexes;

Authorizes a NATO Headquarters as SFOR's successor, to work with EUFOR, under unified command and control;

Recognizes the Peace Agreement's provisions apply to EUFOR and the NATO presence as they did to SFOR;

Intends to consider further authorization as necessary, based on developments;

Authorizes Member States to take measures to ensure compliance with Annexes 1-A and 2, and defend EUFOR and the NATO presence.
The Security Council:

 Authorizes Member States to take measures to ensure compliance with airspace rules over Bosnia and Herzegovina;

 Demands parties respect EUFOR, NATO, and international personnel's security and freedom of movement;

 Requests Member States to report on EUFOR and NATO activities every three months;

 Invites States to provide support and facilities for the operations;

 Reiterates appreciation for the EU Police Mission;

 Requests the Secretary-General to submit reports on the Peace Agreement's implementation;

 Decides to remain seized of the matter.
